1.Explain constructor chaining.
ANS :
	- Constructor chaining is the process of calling one constructor from another constructor within the same 
	- class or from a parent class.
		
	It is done using:
	- this() → Calls constructor of same class	
	- super() → Calls constructor of parent class
	
	Example:
	class Parent {
	    Parent() {
	        System.out.println("Parent constructor");
	    }
	}
	
	class Child extends Parent {
	    Child() {
	        super();   // calls Parent constructor
	        System.out.println("Child constructor");
	    }
	}
	
	- Used to initialize parent class properties.
	- super() must be the first statement in constructor.
	- Helps in code reusability.
	
2 Can a constructor be overridden? 
ANS :
	- No, constructors cannot be overridden.
	Reason:
	- Constructor is not inherited by child class.
	- Overriding happens only when a method is inherited.
	- Constructor name is same as class name, so it cannot be overridden.

3 What is the difference between static and instance variables?
ANS :

	- Static variables belong to the class, whereas instance variables belong to the object.
	- Static variables are shared among all objects, whereas instance variables are separate for each object.
	- Static variables are created only once in memory, whereas instance variables are created every time an object is created.
	- Static variables can be accessed using the class name, whereas instance variables are accessed using object reference.
	- Static variables do not depend on object creation, whereas instance variables depend on object creation.
	- Changes made to a static variable affect all objects, whereas changes made to an instance variable affect only that particular object.

4 What is method hiding? 
ANS :
	- Method hiding occurs when a child class defines a static method with the same name as a static 
	method in parent class.
	- It is different from method overriding.
	
	Example:
	class Parent {
	    static void display() {
	        System.out.println("Parent");
	    }
	}
	
	class Child extends Parent {
	    static void display() {
	        System.out.println("Child");
	    }
	}
	
	If called using:
	Parent obj = new Child();
	obj.display();
	
	Output: Parent
	
	- Why?
	- Because static methods are resolved at compile time (not runtime).
	- This is called method hiding, not overriding.
	
5 What are the limitations of Java?
ANS :
	- No multiple inheritance (with classes)
	- Slower than C/C++ (because of JVM and bytecode)
	- No direct memory management (no pointers)
	- More memory consumption
	- Not suitable for low-level programming (like OS, drivers)
	
	